<div class="col-9">
    <p>
        Carlos's musical journey began with singing in front of hundreds of parishioners at the Cathedral from the
        tender age of 6. He didn't just sing; he accompanied the songs, playing instruments and immersing himself in
        the music. As he grew, so did his musical abilities and the complexity of the music he performed. He
        transitioned from simple melodies to singing harmonies with adult choruses, while also learning to play the
        drum kit.
    </p>
    <p>
        At 12, a new and exciting chapter unfolded as he joined the Zimbabwean marimba band. This unique style of
        marimba demanded that he constantly train his ear, discern new parts, and even compose new mass settings
        with his fellow teenage band members. The band's talent and dedication led them to perform all over Santa
        Fe, including a prestigious engagement at the city's 400th anniversary mass, graced by the presence of the
        King and Queen of Spain.
    </p>
    <p>
        Throughout his percussion journey, Carlos never abandoned his singing. He continued to develop his vocal
        abilities, often asked to sing solo, and his confidence as a singer blossomed. His experiences nurtured a
        well-rounded musician, comfortable both behind a drum kit and at the forefront, captivating audiences with
        his voice.
    </p>
    <p>
        Right when he started university, Carlos joined the Gonzaga Concert Choirs and began voice lessons with
        Darnelle Preston. He got a scholarship that covered the costs and helped with tuition, which was a bit of a
        surprise. Even though he was studying STEM, music became the main thing for him in college. He sang all
        kinds of choral music and got picked to be a soloist a bunch of times. These performances took him all over
        the Northwest to events like NWACDA, NAFME, WMEA, and various concert tours. In his next-to-last year at
        Gonzaga, Carlos joined the Chamber Chorus and the Gonzaga Choir Council, which meant more chances to perform
        and help run things. He really improved his voice under Darnelle Preston and Dr. Timothy Westerhaus,
        developing his own unique style. This all led up to singing Alec Roth’s A New Season for the opening of the
        Myrtle Woldson Performing Arts Center, followed by a month-long tour of Italy. They performed A New Season
        and another full hour of choral music. The tour included workshops with Alec Roth, working with the Luigi
        Cherubini student orchestra and Gonzaga's ballet and theater groups, concerts with local school choirs in
        Florence, Castaglione delle Stiviere, and Cremona, a show with Florence's gay men's chorus Choreos, a
        workshop with opera singers in Florence, and a final concert at the historic Pergola Theater in Florence.
    </p>
    <p>
        After university, Carlos has worked as a professional section leader and soloist with the Cathedral Basilica
        Pontifical Chorus, the chamber chorus Vox Anima, and the Santa Fe Symphony Chorus. He's been a featured
        soloist at the Lensic theater in Santa Fe, New Mexico, singing in Ariel Ramirez’ Misa Criolla and Leonard
        Bernstein’s Chichester Psalms. He’s also done opera workshops for new composers, performed John Rutter’s
        Gloria and Magnificat at Carnegie Hall, and sang at the Cathedral Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi for
        former Governor Bill Richardson's funeral.
    </p>
